        {
            "title": "Leeuwenhoek Year 2023",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 7,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2021
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 7,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2021
                }
            },
            "description": "In 2023 it is 300 years since Antoni van Leeuwenhoek passed away and 350 years since his first letter to the Royal Society launched his long career. Leeuwenhoek's observations and drawings changed the image and understanding of the world around us forever. He discovered, among many other things, bacteria, blood cells and sperm cells. Imagine discovering a totally unknown world. How do you know what you see? How do you show it? And how do you convince others that the world is very different from what they think? Imagining an invisible world is still important today for trust in science.\n\nDuring Antoni van Leeuwenhoek Year, scientists, artists, microscopists, museums, educational institutions and companies throughout the Netherlands will take the public on a discovery through the micro-universe. Activities include several biographies and journal articles as well as international exhibitions at the Rijksmuseum Boerhaave in Leiden and the Royal Society in London, and numerous activities in and around Delft, Leeuwenhoek's hometown. In addition, the final three volumes of Alle de Brieven, the Collected Letters of Antoni van Leeuwenhoek, will be published, bringing to a close this publishing project that began in 1939.",
            "contributors": [
                {
                    "type": "standardizedContributor",
                    "first_name": "Doug",
                    "last_name": "Anderson",
                    "name": null,
                    "headline": "Professor, Medaille University; Guest Researcher, Huygens Institute"
                }
            ]
        },
